<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF108-541-206  </DOCNO><DOCID>08 541 206.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Federal Computer Week  June 4 1990 v4 n22 p39(2).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Into the maelstrom with JTWC. (Joint Typhoon Warning Center)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Lallande, Ann.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>US Air Force and Navy commands at the Joint Typhoon Warning Center(JTWC) on Nimitz Hill in Guam use a sophisticated weather trackingsystem in order to monitor typhoons.andP;  Satellite image analysts usea state-of-the-art computer system to spot a storm, pinpoint thelocation and detail the storm's vital statistics.andP;  The AutomatedTropical Cyclone Forecasting System (ATCFS) was installed threeyears ago by JTWC on a network of Zenith Data Systems Z-248s.andO;ATCFS, originally designed by the Naval Oceanographic andAtmospheric Research Laboratory, reduced the time to issue a stormwarning from 90 minutes to 20 minutes.andP;  The warning center nowwants to upgrade this system for automation of remaininglabor-intensive tasks and integration of all data sources into animproved local area network.andP;  JTWC's biggest integration problemat present is limited 640Kbytes RAM of the Z-248's MS-DOSoperating system.andP;  They hope to replace the existing machines withUnisys microcomputers under a recently awarded Desktop IIIcontract.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     GuamMeteorologyUpgradingLocal Area NetworksState-of-the-ArtUnited States. Air ForceUnited States. Navy.andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>